Functional Requirements
FR1: Project Setup
User creates a “Profile” (local only):
name (optional)
UCI placeholder (optional)
timeframe rule:
“Last 10 years”
“Since age 18”
custom start date
Travel history requirement language commonly references “last 10 years or since 18”. 
Canada
+1
FR2: Travel History Table
Columns (editable, configurable):
From (date)
To (date)
Destination (country, optional city)
Purpose (dropdown + free text)
Notes (optional)
UX requirements:
fast add row
duplicate row
paste multiple rows from clipboard
bulk edit purpose
sort newest to oldest and oldest to newest
FR3: Address History Table
Columns:
From (date)
To (date)
Country
Province/State
City
Address line (optional)
Postal/ZIP (optional)
Notes (optional)
UX requirements:
“Still living here” toggle that sets To = Today (or export date)
IRCC explicitly discusses how to handle “to” dates if you still live at an address. 
IRCC
FR4: Validation And Warnings
Validation runs live and on export. It produces:
Errors (block export unless overridden):
end date before start date
invalid dates
overlaps (two entries covering same time)
Warnings (allow export with acknowledgement):
gaps in coverage within selected timeframe
missing required fields (destination blank)
suspicious micro-gaps (1 day gaps) depending on chosen date boundary rules
IRCC guidance and help content repeatedly emphasize “no gaps” in history tables in certain workflows. 
Canada
+1
FR5: Gap Fix Suggestions
When a gap is detected:
show exact missing range
offer “Add filler entry” button:
Travel: “No travel (in country of residence)” entry
Address: “Same as previous address” or “Unknown, add note” entry
FR6: Export
Export CSV for Travel and Address
Export PDF:
clean table layout with header metadata (Profile name, generated date)
page breaks
repeated table headers per page
optional footnote area for explanations
FR7: Import
Import from CSV (user’s old spreadsheet)
Smart mapping for common column names (From, Start Date, Date From, etc.)
Non-Functional Requirements
Privacy And Security
Offline by default, all data stored locally
“Export only” workflow supported with no account creation
Optional encrypted local database (recommended)
Clear disclaimer: not affiliated with IRCC, no legal advice
Performance
Must handle 2,000+ rows without UI freezing (power users with lots of travel)
Exports under 3 seconds for typical datasets (<300 rows)
Reliability
Auto-save
Versioned backups (local snapshots) so users can roll back changes
User Experience
Primary Screen Layout (One Window)
Top segmented control: Travel | Address | (Personal History later)
Left: table editor
Right: Validation panel
“Errors” section
“Warnings” section
“Fix suggestions” buttons
Bottom bar:
Import
Export CSV
Export PDF
Core Flows
Create profile → choose timeframe rule → start filling table → resolve errors → export
Import old spreadsheet → map columns → validator highlights issues → export
“I don’t remember dates” flow: user enters approximate dates, marks row as “estimated”, validator allows export but flags for review
Data Model (High Level)
Profile
id
name, optional metadata
timeframe rule (start date logic)
Entry (TravelEntry, AddressEntry)
startDate, endDate
fields per table
flags: estimatedDates, notes
Validator produces:
Issue
type (gap, overlap, invalid)
range (start-end)
affected rows
suggestedFix actions
Technical Approach
Option A: macOS App (Recommended For Trust)
SwiftUI UI
Local persistence: SQLite (GRDB) or Core Data
PDF export: PDFKit or custom drawing
Pros:
best privacy story
fast native table editing
Cons:
more Apple-specific development
Option B: Web App (Fastest Iteration)
Next.js or similar
Local-only storage (IndexedDB)
PDF export via client-side library
Pros:
easiest distribution
easiest iteration
Cons:
harder to win trust for sensitive data unless you are very explicit about local-only
MVP Milestones
Milestone 1: Table Editor + CSV Export
Travel and Address tables
Import CSV
Basic validation (date order, overlap, gap detection)
Export CSV
Milestone 2: PDF Export + Fix Suggestions
PDF export with clean pagination
One-click “fill gap” actions
“Today” handling for open-ended entries 
IRCC
Milestone 3: Polish + Packaging
Undo/redo
Keyboard shortcuts
Local backups
Simple onboarding and templates
Success Metrics
Time to first export under 10 minutes for a typical user
Export success rate (no blocking errors) over 80% after first validation pass
Refund rate under 5% if paid
High intent signal: % users who return to edit after import
Monetization (Simple, Realistic)
Free:
unlimited rows
CSV export
Paid (one-time or small annual):
PDF export
gap fix suggestions
multiple profiles
backup/restore
Risks And Mitigations
People interpret it as immigration advice
Mitigation: strong disclaimers, link to relevant IRCC instructions (read-only references) and phrase guidance as “formatting and validation”, not “what you should claim”.
Form and portal requirements vary by stream
Mitigation: keep exports generic “attachment tables”, offer presets but let users customize columns.
Trust barrier due to sensitive data
Mitigation: offline-first, no accounts, transparent “data never leaves your device” design.
If you tell me which platform you want first (macOS app or web app) and whether you want to cover just Travel + Address or also Personal History in v1, I’ll turn this PRD into an implementation checklist with a strict “build this, not that” scope and a data schema you can drop directly into code.